<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="lesson6_1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Exploring Phase</title>

  <p>In this section, we'll distinguish between <em>global phase</em> and <em>relative phase</em>,
    and learn a brand new gate. </p>

  <section xml:id="sec-global-phase">
    <title>Global Phase</title>
    <p> Two quantum states are said to only differ in <term>global phase</term> if you can multiply
      all terms in one state by the <em>same factor</em> to get to the other. For example, the
      following states only differ in global phase, because you can multiply each term by <m>-1</m> to
      get from one to the other:</p>

    <md>
        - \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{00} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{01} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{11}
        \leftrightarrow \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{00} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{01} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{11}
      </md>

    <p> Surprisingly, there is <em>no effective difference if only the global phase is different</em>.
      This might feel a little counterintuitive, but in a quantum system, global phase has no
      physical meaning. We have seen the implication of global phase before (<xref
        ref="sec-simplify-superposition-visual" />): we simply follow our conventions to use the
      form where the leading term has a positive sign. </p>

    <note>
      <p> Global phase always feels a little counterintuitive: how can you just multiply your
        quantum state with <m>-1</m> without any change in its physical meaning? One way to understand
        this is that "global phase" is purely an <em>aspect of our mathematical models</em>. While
        visual representation, bra-ket notation, and vector notation all do a great job of capturing
        the essence of quantum systems, the way we use negative signs is something that is
        introduced by the model.</p>
    </note>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-relative-phase">
    <title>Relative Phase</title>

    <p>In contrast to global phase, two quantum states are said to differ in <term>relative phase</term>
      if you only multiply <em>some</em> of the terms in one state by the same factor to get to the
      other. For example, the following states differ in relative phase, because only the second
      term is multiplied by <m>-1</m> to get from one to the other:</p>

    <md>
        \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}
        \leftrightarrow \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}
      </md>

    <p>A difference in relative phase is a <em>significant difference</em>: the two notations
      represent completely different quantum states. These two states thus have a physical
      difference, and we can design an experiment to distinguish the two states.</p>

    <p>
      <insert>insert question: what kind of experiment can you construct with a measurement
        at the end to distinguish the two states?</insert>
    </p>

    <p> With our new understanding of global and relative phase, we can now see why the <c>Z</c> gate
      only results in a physical effect when the state is in superposition. When the state is a
      basis state, the input and output of the <c>Z</c> gate only differ in global phase. </p>

    <md>
      \ket{1} \xrightarrow{\text{Z}} -\ket{1} = \ket{1}
    </md>

    <p> However, when the state is in superposition, the <c>Z</c> gate introduces a difference in
      relative phase between the input and the output, since a negative phase is only introduced on
      the <m>\ket{1}</m> term.</p>

    <md>
      \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1} \xrightarrow{\text{Z}}
      \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}
    </md>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-cz-gate" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>The <c>CZ</c> Gate</title>
    <sidebyside widths="70% 25%" valign="top">
      <p> Let's take a look at another two-qubit gate, the controlled-<c>Z</c> or <term><c>CZ</c> gate</term>.
        Similar to the <c>CNOT</c> gate, the gate is comprised of a <em>
          control</em> qubit and a <em>target</em> qubit. In this case, if the control is 1, then a <c>Z</c>
        gate is applied to the target. </p>

      <image source="CZ.png" />
    </sidebyside>

    <p> Thus, the only basis state where the <c>CZ</c> gate introduces a change in phase is <m>\ket{11}</m>.
      Note however that the <c>CZ</c> gate can produce interesting results when the inputs are in
      superposition, just like the <c>Z</c> gate does.</p>

